               <floruit notBefore="1892" notAfter="1944">He was a celebrated Ethiopian theologian, grammarian and lexicographer. 
                  Kidāna Wald Kǝfle was born to a family of respected ecclesiastics. While still very young, he
                  was taught calligraphy by his grandfather <roleName type="title">mamhǝr</roleName>
                  <persName ref="PRS10276Yawnatu"/>. 
                  At the age of 20 he left for <placeName ref="LOC3957Jerusa"/>,  in <date>1890</date>, where he lived for 30 years. 
                  In <placeName ref="Q1218"/>, Kidāna Wald Kǝfle
                  was earning a  living by copying manuscripts.  In <placeName ref="Q1218"/>
                  he also learned traditional exegesis (ʾAndǝmtā) from a renowned traditional scholar <persName ref="PRS5907KeflaGi"/>. 
                 Kidāna Wald Kǝfle remained with <persName ref="PRS5907KeflaGi"/> until 
                  the later's death in <date>1908</date>. After he returned to <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop"/> in <date>1920</date>, 
                  he prepared several Gǝʿǝz texts with their Amharic commentaries for the publication. </floruit>
               <death when="1944"/>
                  
                  
